     <h2>
      What we do
     </h2>
     <p>
      Welcome to the Transportation Engineering &amp; Science Program at the University of Tennessee! Transportation impacts many aspects of the world's economy, and has a direct relationship to quality of life.
A variety of transportation challenges exist that have the potential to impact the position of Tennessee and the nation in the global marketplace and economic competitiveness,
as well as to negatively affect the life of the average person in terms of safety, congestion, pollution.
The challenges include mitigating transportation problems while reducing energy consumption and improving the condition of the transportation infrastructure.
Recognizing the need to develop appropriate solutions to transportation problems, the transportation faculty in Civil &amp; Environmental Engineering Department is actively involved in educating the transportation workforce of the future,
conducting research on transportation innovations and disseminating knowledge to researchers and practitioners. We are continuing to expand our research, education,
work force development and technology transfer activities. We are focusing resources in this same thematic area, to address existing and emerging transportation
challenges in the Southeast, across the US, and throughout the world. The University of Tennessee (UT) and Southeastern Transportation Center (STC)
have effectively led university-based activities in USDOT's Region 4 since 1995. The CEE Transportation Engineering &amp; Science Program (TESP)
has the following strengths:
     </p>
     <ul>
      <li>
       A long history of the Transportation engineering and science program and collaborative research relationships established over time.The UTK transportation engineering and science program has a long and distinguished history of leading state and national transportation projects, initiatives, and centers. Especially, the Center for Transportation Research and Southeastern Transportation Center are notable examples of such leadership and are proven research centers. The UTK-Civil &amp; Environmental Engineering faculty has led thecenters. UTK CEE faculty also has collaborative relationships within UTK (CTR research staff, other Engineering Departments, Geography, and Economics), as well as externally with Southeastern Universities and universities nationwide. Interdisciplinary research on innovative strategies is a key aspect of many of these relationships.
       <li>
        Emphasis on scholarship in engineering. TESP faculty is nationally and internationally visible through refereed journal publishing and editorships. Transportation engineering faculty has actively published in archival journals. Additionally, there are currently three journals in transportation where UTK Transportation a faculty member is editor or associate editor. The journal names are: Journal of Intelligent Transportation Systems (SCI-indexed), International Journal of Sustainable Transportation (SCI-Indexed), and the Journal of Transportation Safety and Security.
        <li>
         Leadership in key areas of transportation. UTK is the Flagship University
for the State of Tennessee and as such it provides leadership in key areas with
transportation being one of them. The Tennessee Department of Transportation has
provided direct support for transportation research and education to UTK over
decades. Notably, UTK has distinguished transportation faculty that are research
active, i.e., they publish actively in nationally recognized journals, have
growing citation records, procure research grants from diverse sources,
collaborate with distinguished peers/colleagues, and conduct innovative research
(besides teaching and mentoring students). It is noteworthy that Dr. Chris
Cherry has received the National Science Foundation (NSF) Career Award,
reflecting his distinction in research on transportation issues, especially in
the area of sustainability.
         <li>
          Faculty and students are involved in international collaborations. The UTK
transportation engineering faculty has several active international linkages in
a number of countries that include China, Portugal, and South Korea to name a
few. Their collaborations with international universities and in particular
production of research in collaboration with other countries distinguish them.
          <li>
           Proximity to Oak Ridge National Lab (ORNL). The presence of Oak Ridge
National Lab, especially the Center for Transportation Analysis, provides
research and developments in energy and transportation.
           <li>
            To achieve comprehensive transportation safety in our region, STC strives to understand its sociology,
demography, and safety cultures; gather and curate relevant data; take advantage of emerging connectivity
between vehicles and infrastructure; integrate human factors with infrastructure use; implement and enrich
the Highway Safety Manual and similar tools; and apply these to all operations related to moving people and goods.
           </li>
          </li>
         </li>
        </li>
       </li>
      </li>
     </ul>
     <h2>
      Mission and Goals
     </h2>
     <p>
      The missions of the UTK Transportation Engineering and Science Program (TESP)
are to contribute to the advancement of transportation in three ways:
     </p>
     <ul>
      <li>
       Education: The education of future and current transportation
    professionals is a key mission. The basic purpose is to introduce
    undergraduate and graduate students to transportation and associated
    problems and approaches that have been undertaken or proposed to solve those
    problems. Another important aim is to enhance our internationally recognized
    graduate program that trains students from diverse backgrounds as
    professionals who plan, design and operate multimodal transportation systems
    in both domestic and international settings.
       <li>
        Research: The development of knowledge that expands our current body of
transportation engineering knowledge and stimulates applications of new
strategies/technologies, involving planning, design and operations of the
transportation system. Our contribution to further development of the
transportation engineering profession through applied research is important.
        <li>
         Public service: Our commitment to knowledge transfer and public service is
meant to provide immediate benefits to the university, citizens of the state of
Tennessee, the nation, and a number of countries. Important aspects are
dissemination of knowledge to transportation practitioners and other
stakeholders, student internships in government agencies, and student and
faculty involvement in Transportation Research Board, Institute of
Transportation Engineers and American Society of Civil Engineers activities, and
editorships of journals.
        </li>
       </li>
      </li>
     </ul>
